Gilbert Arenas pointed at a laser-printed
document taped to the wall of the Golden State Warriors' locker
room. It was a list of the Western Conference's teams and their
records before and after the All-Star break.
article.headline: Arenas, Richardson spark surging Warriors
article.linkText: Warriors continue strong against East, pound Hawks
article.story:
OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Gilbert Arenas pointed at a laser-printed document taped to the wall of the Golden State Warriors' locker room. It was a list of the Western Conference's teams and their records before and after the All-Star break.
Richardson

Arenas

"You see this list right here?'' Arenas asked, pointing at the post-break records. "If we can stay in the top of this list, we can still make the playoffs.'' Playoff talk in Oakland has been a joke for eight years -- but these days, nobody's laughing quite as loudly. Arenas had 18 points and six assists, and Jason Richardson scored 20 points as the Warriors stayed strong at home, beating the Atlanta Hawks 115-93 Sunday night. Progress comes in steps, and the Warriors are showing more positive signs by the week in coach Eric Musselman's first season. The Warriors are in 10th place in the conference, and they demolished the weary Hawks quickly and decisively -- just as a good team should. Antawn Jamison scored 17 points as Golden State improved to 10-2 against the Eastern Conference in Oakland, where it has won five of its last seven games. "Our defense continues to make progress,'' Musselman said. "I think guys are starting to take on more individual battles now -- taking on premier scorers from other teams.'' The Warriors built an 18-point lead in the third quarter on the way to a rare blowout victory. Then they faced yet another challenge in the long season: mechanical problems with their team plane, delaying their late-night flight to Denver for Monday's game. Richardson, the two-time defending NBA slam dunk champion, punctuated an explosive game with back-to-back dunks in the third quarter -- the first in the face of Hawks shot-blocker Theo Ratliff, and the second with a 360-degree flourish on a breakaway. Shareef Abdur-Rahim had 23 points and 14 rebounds for Atlanta, which lost for the sixth time in eight games. Glenn Robinson scored 21 points on 7-of-24 shooting, but on the third stop of their season-long seven-game road trip, the Hawks appeared tired from Saturday night's tight victory over the Los Angeles Clippers. "They beat us in all phases of the game, and we didn't shoot the ball well,'' said Jason Terry, who had 19 points and seven assists -- and seven turnovers. "Coach Musselman, from Day 1, has been doing an excellent job with that group. He knows his talent, and that's a good team that we just played.'' Troy Murphy had 17 points and 19 rebounds for the Warriors, who played a tough defensive game against the Hawks' stars. Eight Golden State players also scored at least eight points. Though the Warriors remain the uptempo, shoot-first team Musselman promised to field, their defense is noticeably better than it was earlier in the season -- or in the previous two seasons under coaches Dave Cowens and Brian Winters. "It's getting to the point where it's enjoyable to play defense, because it leads to a lot of easy baskets for us now,'' Jamison said. The Hawks shot just 33 percent -- barely higher than their worst shooting game of the season. Robinson seemed more preoccupied with the hecklers in the front row at the Arena, while Ratliff went 1-for-8 from the floor and blocked just one shot. "They're an explosive young team,'' Hawks coach Terry Stotts said. "They were creating a few turnovers and getting out in transition, and their activity got us out of our rhythm. Once they got the lead, we couldn't get back into it.'' Hawks forward Nazr Mohammed missed the game with a foot injury. He'll be examined in Oakland on Monday to determine whether he has another stress fracture in his foot, which forced him to miss the first 20 games of the season. Game notes
Musselman spent the previous two seasons as an assistant to former Atlanta coach Lon Kruger, who was fired last December. ... Abdur-Rahim played one college season in nearby Berkeley. ... Actor Delroy Lindo, an Arena regular, sat in the front row. ... Golden State swept the season series from Atlanta for just the third time in the last 20 years. ... Murphy is one of just five NBA players averaging at least 10 points and 10 rebounds per game. The other four were All-Stars: Kevin Garnett, Tim Duncan, Elton Brand and Jermaine O'Neal.
